[1] UK (Scotland)
Date: Tue 15 Aug 2017
Source: The Scotsman [edited]
http://www.scotsman.com/business/companies/farming/warning-over-virus-infection-threat-to-cereal-harvest-1-4532170


A warning has been issued over [a] virus infection threat to cereal harvests. Growers should be aware of the higher risks of barley yellow dwarf virus (BYDV) infection in crops sown this autumn [2017] and were advised by Hutchinsons' [Crop Consultants] Cam Murray to make every effort to mitigate the possible impacts.

He said that pressure in several areas of Scotland had been "excessive" after large flights of aphids through spring, with classic yellowing symptoms found in spring oats, barley, and wheat. "This means that early-sown winter barley crops will be at particularly high risk this autumn," he said. The most effective way to protect early growth was to use a seed treatment and well-timed follow-up spray.

[Byline: Brian Henderson]

